`ctx-cage/src` is the whole ctx-cage crate: a sandbox that runs an agent subprocess with no network access except a proxied API relay, a masked filesystem, and fresh Linux namespaces, then guarantees teardown. Depending on this crate gets you either the three binaries in `bin/` (host launchers + in-cage broker client) or, if embedding, the `lifecycle::execute(&Resolved) -> Result<i32, CageError>` entry point directly plus `bwrap::build_bwrap_args` for constructing the sandbox argv yourself.

The crate splits cleanly along the cage boundary. Host side: `cli.rs` resolves flags into a `lifecycle::Mode` and enforces the spend gate; `bwrap/` turns a `BwrapConfig` into bwrap argv (workspace RW at real host path, toolchain RO, secrets masked, network off except the proxy socket); `runtime.rs` resolves the host `claude` binary and synthesizes a minimal `~/.claude.json` for billed/subscription launches; `proxy.rs` is the sole egress, forwarding the in-cage relay's UNIX-socket traffic to the real API over TLS (via `socat`, not a TLS crate), injecting the real API key host-side when in passthrough mode; `lifecycle/` sequences prepare→run/serve→teardown, choosing between `proxy`-backed (billed) and `broker`-backed (tool-brokered) run paths. Guest side: `ctx_cage_client.rs` (in `bin/`) and `broker.rs`/`spawn.rs`/`protocol.rs` implement the tool-broker mode — the client sends framed JSON requests over `protocol.rs`'s wire format, `broker.rs` allowlist-checks and dispatches via `spawn.rs`'s `Spawner` trait, denied/failed tools get fixed exit codes (94/95). `summarize.rs` is a separate concern: post-run `.ctx` leaf regeneration, invoked by `ctx-run` (bin) after a session, not part of the sandbox mechanism itself.

Cross-cutting facts an editor must hold: `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` never enters cage env in either run mode — auth is either the bound credentials file (runtime.rs) or the proxy's header injection (proxy.rs), because setting the var triggers an interactive login prompt that breaks headless runs. `target_root` is canonicalized once and used verbatim everywhere (ADR-046) — bwrap binds, claude's trust-map key in `runtime.rs`, and lifecycle's git-dirty check all assume the same real host path with no alias. Secrets/masks are always empty regular files, never `/dev/null`, because binds are `nodev`. `error.rs`'s single `CageError` is the return type threaded through every module boundary (`Io`, `Json`, `Protocol`); modules needing richer errors define their own `Result` type layered on top rather than extending this enum. `lib.rs`'s `CAGE_RULES_MD` (compiled-in agent doctrine) must be injected via `--append-system-prompt-file` on every real `claude` launch — any new launcher path must preserve that.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.